 its liabilities as they come due.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF QUICK RATIO\":\"An international food retailer, which regularly reports a current ratio of about 0.3, illustrates the fallacy of using a single current ratio target to indicate satisfactory liquidity. The company has low inventory, as food only lasts a few days. It has few receivables, as most of its sales are for cash. It invests cash balances in non-current assets and holds low cash balances. Also, the company does not pay its suppliers for three months, so it has large payables balances. Far from indicating liquidity problems, the company uses its suppliers as a free source of financing.\"", "\"WAYS TO INCREASE LIQUIDITY RATIOS\":\"Acceptable ways of increasing (i.e., improving) liquidity ratios include using long-term finance (loans and equity) to finance acquisitions of non-current assets, generating positive cash flows to repay short-term liabilities on time. Liquidity ratios may also be increased by adjusting year-end balances ('window dressing'); however, this is not a genuine improvement.\"", "\"QUIZ: QUICK RATIO (WINDOW DRESSING)\":\"This quiz involves calculating the quick ratio from given financial data and re-calculating it after making payments just before the year-end. It helps in understanding the impact of 'window dressing' on liquidity ratios.\"", "\"GEARING\":\"Gearing (or 'leverage') measures the portion of a company's finance provided by debt. The advantage of debt is that it is a relatively cheap source of financing. Providers of debt require a lower return than providers of equity finance because they face less risk, as they receive preferential repayment in the event of default. Interest on debt is also a tax-deductible expense, which further reduces the cost of debt. However, companies with too much debt (gearing) increase the risk of being unable to repay the debt's interest and principal.\"", "\"GEARING RATIOS\":Gearing Ratios are financial performance indicators that measure the proportion of an organization's capital that is financed by debt. These ratios specifically assess the proportion of long-term borrowed funds, which pay a fixed return, relative to equity capital, also known as shareholders' funds. Gearing Ratios provide critical information about a company's financial risk due to its debt burden. Two commonly used Gearing Ratios are: Equity/Debt * 100, which gives gearing as a percentage, and Debt/Equity plus debt * 100.", "\"DELIVERY PERFORMANCE\":\"Delivery performance is measured by the percentage of orders delivered within 30 minutes. It is an essential aspect of the quality of service.\"", "\"CUSTOMER RATINGS\":\"Customer ratings are scores given by customers to rate the quality of meals and service. These ratings provide insight into customer satisfaction and perceived quality.\"", "\"ONLINE SALES\":\"Online sales refer to the number of sales made through the company's website. It is an important metric for assessing the effectiveness of the online platform.\"", "\"WEBSITE VISITS\":\"Website visits refer to the number of times the company's website is accessed by users. It indicates the level of interest and visibility of the website.\"", "\"COMPLAINTS\":\"Complaints\" are expressions of dissatisfaction from customers regarding the service or product quality. The number of complaints can indicate areas needing improvement. Recently, the number of complaints has increased significantly, rising by 283% from 12 to 46. Additionally, complaints per customer visit have increased from 0.15% (12 complaints out of 8,000 visits) to 0.45% (46 complaints out of 10,225 visits).", "\"STAFF TURNOVER\":\"Staff turnover is the rate at which employees leave the company and are replaced. Low staff turnover is a positive sign indicating employee satisfaction and stability. Additionally, staff turnover is used as a metric in quizzes to assess the element of value for money.\"", "\"STAFF UTILISATION\":\"Staff utilisation is calculated by dividing the number of meals sold by the number of staff. It measures how effectively the staff is being used.\"", "\"NON-FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT\":\"Non-financial performance assessment involves evaluating aspects of a business that are not directly related to financial metrics, such as customer satisfaction, service quality, and employee performance.\"", "\"TRAINING FOR CUSTOMER SERVICE\":\"Training to ensure staff understand the importance of customer service. It helps improve performance in customer service.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}